using SkiaSharp;

var fontPath = "/System/Library/Fonts/Supplemental/Arial Black.ttf";
Console.WriteLine($"Loading font from: {fontPath}");

using var stream = File.OpenRead(fontPath);
var typeface = SKTypeface.FromStream(stream);

if (typeface == null)
{
    Console.WriteLine("ERROR: Failed to load typeface from stream");
    return 1;
}

Console.WriteLine($"Loaded typeface: FamilyName={typeface.FamilyName}, Style={typeface.FontStyle}");

#pragma warning disable CS0618
var matchedNormal = SKFontManager.Default.MatchTypeface(typeface, SKFontStyle.Normal);
var matchedBold = SKFontManager.Default.MatchTypeface(typeface, SKFontStyle.Bold);
var matchedItalic = SKFontManager.Default.MatchTypeface(typeface, SKFontStyle.Italic);
#pragma warning restore CS0618

Console.WriteLine($"MatchTypeface(Normal): {(matchedNormal == null ? "NULL" : matchedNormal.FamilyName)}");
Console.WriteLine($"MatchTypeface(Bold): {(matchedBold == null ? "NULL" : matchedBold.FamilyName)}");
Console.WriteLine($"MatchTypeface(Italic): {(matchedItalic == null ? "NULL" : matchedItalic.FamilyName)}");

if (matchedNormal == null || matchedBold == null || matchedItalic == null)
{
    Console.WriteLine("BUG CONFIRMED: MatchTypeface returned null for at least one style");
    return 1;
}

Console.WriteLine("SUCCESS: All MatchTypeface calls returned non-null");
return 0;

proposedResponse.body:
Thanks for the detailed repro! We were able to reproduce this.

`SKFontManager.MatchTypeface` returns `null` for all typefaces on macOS — not just custom fonts loaded via `FromStream`, but also system fonts loaded via `FromFamilyName`. This method was marked `[Obsolete]` in SkiaSharp 2.x because it did not work reliably across platforms, and it has been **removed entirely in SkiaSharp 3.x**.

**Tested versions:**
| Version | Result |
|---------|--------|
| 2.88.3 (reported) | ❌ MatchTypeface returns null |
| 2.88.9 (latest 2.x) | ❌ MatchTypeface returns null |
| 3.119.2 (latest 3.x) | API removed (CS1061) |

**Workaround:** Use `SKFontManager.Default.MatchFamily(familyName, style)` instead:

```csharp
// Instead of:
// var bold = SKFontManager.Default.MatchTypeface(typeface, SKFontStyle.Bold);

// Use:
var bold = SKFontManager.Default.MatchFamily(typeface.FamilyName, SKFontStyle.Bold);
```

Note that `MatchFamily` only searches **system-installed fonts**. For custom fonts in Blazor WASM (where no system fonts exist), you'll need to load each style variant separately:

```csharp
var regular = SKTypeface.FromStream(assembly.GetManifestResourceStream("App.tahoma.ttf"));
var bold = SKTypeface.FromStream(assembly.GetManifestResourceStream("App.tahomabd.ttf"));
```

For the best experience, we recommend upgrading to SkiaSharp 3.x, which makes these patterns clearer by removing the non-functional `MatchTypeface` API.
